From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Keyur Maru <kd2maru@gmail.com>
Date: Mon, 13 Jul 2026 05:27:48 -0700
Subject: [PATCH] Bluetooth: exit cleanly when the vendor HAL reports
 controller init failure

The HIDL backend asserts on a non-SUCCESS initializationComplete status, which
raises SIGABRT inside com.android.bluetooth. On a port whose controller cannot
be brought up at all (the vendor HAL reports "Controller Init failed"), that
tombstone is counted as a native crash: BluetoothManagerService restarts the
stack, it aborts again, and PackageWatchdog/RescueParty escalates and can end up
rebooting the device.

The GD startup path has no clean "HAL failed to start -> disable" route, and
faking SUCCESS just moves the abort to the HCI-reset timeout. So when the vendor
HAL says the controller is unusable, log it and _Exit(0) instead: at the binder
layer this looks the same to BluetoothManagerService, which runs its bounded
retry/backoff and then leaves the adapter cleanly OFF, but with no SIGABRT, no
tombstone and no crash accounting. Devices whose controller initializes normally
never take this branch.
---
 system/gd/hal/hci_backend_hidl.cc | 35 ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++-
 1 file changed, 34 insertions(+), 1 deletion(-)

diff --git a/system/gd/hal/hci_backend_hidl.cc b/system/gd/hal/hci_backend_hidl.cc
index 96bc1a042e..9103a02e14 100644
--- a/system/gd/hal/hci_backend_hidl.cc
+++ b/system/gd/hal/hci_backend_hidl.cc
@@ -20,6 +20,8 @@
 #include <bluetooth/log.h>
 #include <com_android_bluetooth_flags.h>
 
+#include <cstdlib>
+
 #include "common/stop_watch.h"
 #include "common/watchdog.h"
 #include "hal/hci_backend.h"
@@ -44,7 +46,38 @@ public:
 
   using HidlStatus = ::android::hardware::bluetooth::V1_0::Status;
   Return<void> initializationComplete(HidlStatus status) override {
-    log::assert_that(status == HidlStatus::SUCCESS, "status == HidlStatus::SUCCESS");
+    // Graceful degradation for hardware bring-up.
+    //
+    // On some ports the vendor Bluetooth controller cannot be brought up at all
+    // (e.g. the Qualcomm WCNSS/pronto subsystem is not loaded on this device, so
+    // the controller never returns a valid build version and the vendor HAL
+    // reports "Controller Init failed" / status != SUCCESS here).
+    //
+    // Upstream unconditionally LOG(FATAL)s on a non-SUCCESS status. That raises
+    // SIGABRT inside com.android.bluetooth, producing a tombstone that
+    // PackageWatchdog/RescueParty counts as a native crash. Repeated across the
+    // BluetoothManagerService restart attempts this escalates RescueParty and
+    // can reboot the device.
+    //
+    // The Bluetooth stack has no clean "HAL failed to start -> disable" path
+    // (the whole GD startup is built on fatal asserts), and faking SUCCESS only
+    // moves the abort to the subsequent HCI-reset timeout. So when the vendor
+    // HAL tells us the controller is unusable, exit the process cleanly instead
+    // of aborting: at the binder layer this is indistinguishable from a crash,
+    // so BluetoothManagerService still runs its bounded retry/backoff and then
+    // leaves the adapter cleanly OFF (MAX_ERROR_RESTART_RETRIES) -- but with no
+    // SIGABRT, no tombstone, and no RescueParty crash accounting. This branch is
+    // a no-op on devices whose controller initializes normally.
+    if (status != HidlStatus::SUCCESS) {
+      log::error(
+              "Bluetooth controller initialization failed (status={}). The vendor "
+              "HAL reports the controller is not usable on this device; shutting "
+              "down Bluetooth gracefully instead of aborting.",
+              static_cast<uint32_t>(status));
+      // Clean, immediate exit: no signal, no atexit/global destructors, no
+      // tombstone. Not counted as a crash by PackageWatchdog/RescueParty.
+      std::_Exit(0);
+    }
     callbacks_->initializationComplete();
     return Void();
   }
